00:05:15.420 --> 00:05:20.030
So the anti-trafficking provisions
of section 1201 are not part

00:05:20.030 --> 00:05:22.830
of the triennial rulemaking,
as I think you know.

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:25.720
But they are generally provisions
upon both access controls

00:05:25.720 --> 00:05:29.750
and section 1201(b), which
applies to copy controls.

00:05:29.750 --> 00:05:32.910
In many of the comments we
received, we heard arguments

00:05:32.910 --> 00:05:36.840
that the intended beneficiaries
of exemptions to the provision

00:05:36.840 --> 00:05:42.850 position:56%
on circumvention are difficult for
the intended beneficiaries to engage

00:05:42.850 --> 00:05:45.060
in without assistance
from third parties.

00:05:45.060 --> 00:05:48.830
And the most recent rulemaking, the
Register of copy Rights recommended

00:05:48.830 --> 00:05:52.420
to the Librarian some of the
difficulties that have arisen

00:05:52.420 --> 00:05:53.950
with anti-trafficking provision.

00:05:53.950 --> 00:05:57.240
She stated, "Congress may wish
to consider clarifications

00:05:57.240 --> 00:06:00.790 position:56%
to section 1201 to ensure that the
beneficiaries of exemptions are able

00:06:00.790 --> 00:06:02.090
to take full advantage of them,

00:06:02.090 --> 00:06:04.640
even if they need assistance
from third parties.

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:07.490
While the anti-trafficking
provisions can curtail bad actors

00:06:07.490 --> 00:06:10.090
seeking to profit from
circumvention by others,

00:06:10.090 --> 00:06:12.940
they also constrain the ability
that allows third parties

00:06:12.940 --> 00:06:15.630
to offer assistance
to exempted users."

00:06:15.630 --> 00:06:21.020
So as the first question to kickoff
I think rather broadly is how

00:06:21.020 --> 00:06:24.250
effective are the participants
feeling that the provisions are--

00:06:24.250 --> 00:06:26.400
the anti-trafficking
provisions have been

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:29.770
at encouraging the innovative
digital distribution to models

00:06:29.770 --> 00:06:33.000
