00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:22.480
&gt;&gt; June Besek: Right.

00:19:22.480 --> 00:19:24.870
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Just to
sort of follow up on that,

00:19:24.870 --> 00:19:29.260
and I think this picks up on
something that Mr. Love said,

00:19:29.260 --> 00:19:34.790
we had a lot of comments drawing
the distinction between devices--

00:19:34.790 --> 00:19:36.310
circumvention devices and services.

00:19:36.310 --> 00:19:40.350
And there was a lot of concern
expressed about the need

00:19:40.350 --> 00:19:47.660
for beneficiaries of exemptions
to use or just seek assistance

00:19:47.660 --> 00:19:50.350
from third parties in
order for the exemptions

00:19:50.350 --> 00:19:51.670
to have any practical effect.

00:19:51.670 --> 00:19:58.070
I wonder just from your experience,
to what extent is that a concern?

00:19:58.070 --> 00:20:01.150
Have you seen that out
in the marketplace?

00:20:01.150 --> 00:20:05.570
And if so, to what extent should
the law recognize that sort

00:20:05.570 --> 00:20:11.090
of distinction and what would you
suggest could be done about it?

00:20:11.090 --> 00:20:13.420
I believe Mr. Adler was next.

00:20:13.420 --> 00:20:15.400
If you'll-- I know you
may have had a comment

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:18.310
about the previous question, but
feel free to address this as well.

00:20:18.310 --> 00:20:19.610
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: Yeah.

00:20:19.610 --> 00:20:21.180 position:56%
I think that the real problem here--

00:20:21.180 --> 00:20:24.830
it's not so much distinguishing
between levels of protection

00:20:24.830 --> 00:20:26.740
for different types of works.

00:20:26.740 --> 00:20:30.150
I mean, the issue of dealing
with embedded software

00:20:30.150 --> 00:20:34.740
in consumer products and the
functionality issue with respect

00:20:34.740 --> 00:20:39.640
to driving those products,
again, should not become the tail

00:20:39.640 --> 00:20:43.730
that wags the anti-circumvention
dog because the issue

00:20:43.730 --> 00:20:46.260 position:56%
for anti-circumvention was primarily

00:20:46.260 --> 00:20:50.210
about protecting access
to expressive works.

00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:54.950
And the problem with that is, in
response to what Jamie suggested,

00:20:54.950 --> 00:21:00.670 position:56%
is simply that there's no way to
allow for the dissemination of tools

00:21:00.670 --> 00:21:05.750
that only enable the exercise
of exemptions or other kinds

00:21:05.750 --> 00:21:08.030
of authorized circumventions.

00:21:08.030 --> 00:21:11.360
Let me give you an analogy when we
talk about third-party assistance.

00:21:11.360 --> 00:21:15.410
In most jurisdictions, if you want
to go into business as a locksmith

00:21:15.410 --> 00:21:19.320 position:56%
or if you want to seek employment as
a locksmith, you have to be bonded.

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:20.700
You have to be certified.

00:21:20.700 --> 00:21:22.200
You have to be licensed.

00:21:22.200 --> 00:21:23.990
And the tools that you're able

00:21:23.990 --> 00:21:27.430
to acquire are very carefully
regulated and tracked.

00:21:27.430 --> 00:21:31.810
And those are mechanical tools,
very distinctive types of tools.

00:21:31.810 --> 00:21:34.960
What we're talking about in the
online world, when we're talking

00:21:34.960 --> 00:21:39.770 position:56%
about circumventing various types of
technological protection measures,

00:21:39.770 --> 00:21:43.230
we're primarily talking about
software acting on software

00:21:43.230 --> 00:21:47.200
or we're talking about things
like random number generators

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:51.160
that are going to try to find the
proper password or the combination

00:21:51.160 --> 00:21:56.850 position:56%
for the authentication key that
allows somebody to access the works.

00:21:56.850 --> 00:22:00.660
And it's clear that those
types of things are going

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:03.890
to have many legitimate uses
as well as they're going

00:22:03.890 --> 00:22:07.460
to have these types
of illegitimate uses.

00:22:07.460 --> 00:22:10.710
And it seems that it's going to
be extremely difficult to be able

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:15.510
to identify them, to be able to
regulate them, to be able to ensure

00:22:15.510 --> 00:22:18.450
that the people who would
be authorized to use them

00:22:18.450 --> 00:22:24.660
to perform circumventions are
in fact also properly regulated.

00:22:25.830 --> 00:22:27.130
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:22:27.130 --> 00:22:28.810
Mr. Greenstein?

00:22:28.810 --> 00:22:30.570
&gt;&gt; Seth Greenstein: Thank you.

00:22:30.570 --> 00:22:33.170
So there are a few issues
here I'd like to address

00:22:33.170 --> 00:22:34.470
from the past few questions.

00:22:34.470 --> 00:22:38.430
So I appreciated Mr. Adler trying
to draw the distinction between,

00:22:38.430 --> 00:22:42.170
you know, access to expressive
works versus trying to get access

00:22:42.170 --> 00:22:46.390
to the functional aspects of the
work or the aspects of a software

00:22:46.390 --> 00:22:49.320
that control function and
have no other purpose.

00:22:49.320 --> 00:22:52.220
And I think that really is
a line that is easy to draw.

00:22:52.220 --> 00:22:55.740
I mean, where the software
interoperates with the part,

00:22:55.740 --> 00:22:58.250
controls the part and is
really part of the part.

00:22:58.250 --> 00:22:59.690
It's inseparable from the part.

00:22:59.690 --> 00:23:01.980
I think what we're talking about,

00:23:01.980 --> 00:23:05.890
the ability to circumvent a
technological protection measure

00:23:05.890 --> 00:23:09.200
to get access to the
work is really all

00:23:09.200 --> 00:23:13.320
about repairing the functionality,
augmenting the functionality,

00:23:13.320 --> 00:23:16.580
customizing the functionality
and not anything having to do

00:23:16.580 --> 00:23:18.690 position:56%
with the expressiveness of the work.

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:21.940
Some of these software, in fact,
may not be copyrightable at all.

00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:24.760
There's one case in
the Ford versus Autel,

00:23:24.760 --> 00:23:28.210
where the court basically found
this is not copyrightable--

00:23:28.210 --> 00:23:31.490 position:56%
the elements that you're trying to
get access to are not copyrightable.

00:23:31.490 --> 00:23:33.420 position:56%
And the same was true in the Lexmark

00:23:33.420 --> 00:23:34.890
versus Static Control
Components case,

00:23:34.890 --> 00:23:38.240
where they found the software
was not protectable by copyright.

00:23:38.240 --> 00:23:41.350
So that's one issue.

00:23:41.350 --> 00:23:45.140
Looking at the real object of
protection here, the real object

00:23:45.140 --> 00:23:48.800
of protection is not
the expressive nature

00:23:48.800 --> 00:23:50.430
of the software, the software code.

00:23:50.430 --> 00:23:53.530
The real object of protection
is the functionality provided

00:23:53.530 --> 00:23:56.340
and stopping others from
repairing that functionality,

00:23:56.340 --> 00:24:02.790
stopping competition in the
repair of consumer products.

00:24:02.790 --> 00:24:06.760
And that being the case, I mean,
it's really an interesting question

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:11.990
as to whether section 1201(a)
actually applies or (a)(1)

00:24:11.990 --> 00:24:18.200
or (a)(2) really applies because
the consumer owns the work--

00:24:18.200 --> 00:24:22.310
I mean, owns the product
and has the right of access

00:24:22.310 --> 00:24:24.640
to all the functionality
provided by the product.

00:24:24.640 --> 00:24:27.450
So is there really
an issue with access?

00:24:27.450 --> 00:24:31.350
The consumer has authorized access
to the functionality provided

00:24:31.350 --> 00:24:34.010
by the software and that is the
only purpose of the software.

00:24:34.010 --> 00:24:38.160 position:56%
So I would say a good argument could
be made that there's no 1201(a)(1)

00:24:38.160 --> 00:24:43.720
or (a)(2) issue to begin with and
the same would be true for (b).

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:45.880
Lastly, I do want to address one
of the points that you raised

00:24:45.880 --> 00:24:50.410
with respect to the differences
between devices and services.

00:24:50.410 --> 00:24:53.310
I think you cannot
make that distinction,

00:24:53.310 --> 00:24:55.850
particularly for the
auto repair industry,

00:24:55.850 --> 00:24:59.350
simply because not every mom
and pop shop-- repair shop--

00:24:59.350 --> 00:25:03.430
is going to have the ability
to develop the software

00:25:03.430 --> 00:25:07.870 position:56%
that circumvents, that is able to
then repair the software in the car.

00:25:07.870 --> 00:25:12.720
But everyone should be able
to use a tool that is provided

00:25:12.720 --> 00:25:15.110
by someone else, developed
by somebody else that enables

00:25:15.110 --> 00:25:18.230
that repair, which is why I think
you cannot really make the divide

00:25:18.230 --> 00:25:19.880
based on devices versus services.

00:25:19.880 --> 00:25:23.270
So I think the divide really
has to be between protection

00:25:23.270 --> 00:25:27.690
of functionality versus
protection of expression.

00:25:27.690 --> 00:25:28.990
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Thank you.

