00:42:02.760 --> 00:42:07.730 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Anyone else want to--
Well, Mr. Love can respond to that

00:42:07.730 --> 00:42:10.890
or to the previous question.

00:42:10.890 --> 00:42:16.120
&gt;&gt; James Love: Allan
Adler brought up the issue

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:17.460
of regulation of locksmiths.

00:42:17.460 --> 00:42:20.970 position:56%
I think that's something that
people probably should take a harder

00:42:20.970 --> 00:42:22.270
look at.

00:42:22.270 --> 00:42:26.320
If-- I don't think locksmiths
are really regulated everywhere.

00:42:26.320 --> 00:42:29.360
But I think that in some
states, they definitely are.

00:42:29.360 --> 00:42:32.360 position:56%
And I think the idea that you'd have
people that have access to tools

00:42:32.360 --> 00:42:33.900
that are not generally
available and that

00:42:33.900 --> 00:42:36.260
in some cases they're
posting bonds--

00:42:36.260 --> 00:42:38.790
you know, or the authorities
are aware of who they are.

00:42:38.790 --> 00:42:40.540
They have certain responsibilities
and that--

00:42:40.540 --> 00:42:45.020
and that they're reputable
citizens is sort of a--

00:42:45.020 --> 00:42:46.930
makes a lot of sense in
that particular area.

00:42:46.930 --> 00:42:50.510
And it may make sense in this
area in terms of the things.

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:52.110
I mean, you could imagine
a situation

00:42:52.110 --> 00:42:56.510
where libraries develop
their own standards for sort

00:42:56.510 --> 00:43:01.070
of a self-regulatory-type
proposal where they could sort

00:43:01.070 --> 00:43:05.580
of imagine practices that
were reasonable and limited

00:43:05.580 --> 00:43:09.530
to the purposes to which
they're authorized to use works

00:43:09.530 --> 00:43:14.970
under exceptions and where that
could-- That could flourish.

00:43:14.970 --> 00:43:17.310
I think the problem is
you have this lobbying

00:43:17.310 --> 00:43:24.110
from the motion picture industry,
the database industry, you know,

00:43:24.110 --> 00:43:29.070
a few sectors of the economy, maybe
people with operating software

00:43:29.070 --> 00:43:31.440
that were commercial products,
mass market type products

00:43:31.440 --> 00:43:35.600
for DRM protection and, you know,
back in 1996 and things like that.

00:43:35.600 --> 00:43:39.250
And then, you have these laws that
just sweep everything into it.

00:43:39.250 --> 00:43:44.470
And I think that what would have
been better is if sectors that felt

00:43:44.470 --> 00:43:47.260
that they deserved to
have the state intervene

00:43:47.260 --> 00:43:51.070
and make things illegal would
themselves make the case

00:43:51.070 --> 00:43:53.880
that motion pictures deserve
some kind of protection

00:43:53.880 --> 00:43:58.190
or it may be other types of works
do as opposed to just starting

00:43:58.190 --> 00:44:00.630
with the assumption that
everyone automatically,

00:44:00.630 --> 00:44:03.080
no matter what the context
is, basically gets it.

00:44:03.080 --> 00:44:05.180
So I think you should
have to make that case

00:44:05.180 --> 00:44:06.480
that the state should
have to intervene.

00:44:06.480 --> 00:44:09.460
And in terms of the cost of
some of these systems in terms

00:44:09.460 --> 00:44:13.390
of managing the cost
of differentiation,

00:44:13.390 --> 00:44:17.130
I think it would be reasonable
that the people seeking the state

00:44:17.130 --> 00:44:22.490
to provide the legal protection
could pay money to have--

00:44:22.490 --> 00:44:26.150
to share some of the cost of
administering these systems,

00:44:26.150 --> 00:44:30.910
which are extensive, and that the
people that are seeking to operate

00:44:30.910 --> 00:44:33.960
as providing services, they could
also bear some of the cost as well.

00:44:33.960 --> 00:44:37.250
I mean, that could be kind
of an approach you might look

00:44:37.250 --> 00:44:38.550
in some of the other areas.

00:44:38.550 --> 00:44:43.080
The other thing I'd like to call
attention to is that EFF submitted

00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:50.380
on April 21st, 2016 in the-- the
Food and Drug Administration,

00:44:50.380 --> 00:44:52.880
they submitted comments
on management

00:44:52.880 --> 00:44:56.370 position:56%
of cybersecurity in medical devices.

00:44:56.370 --> 00:45:01.850
And they described I think are
quite important some of the growth

00:45:01.850 --> 00:45:05.210
of security interests and problems
that you have in medical devices

00:45:05.210 --> 00:45:08.970
that are implanted in your body,
which could kill you, that--

00:45:08.970 --> 00:45:11.930
you know, where these issues
of DMCA protection come up.

00:45:11.930 --> 00:45:15.730
It's just an example of how
far out-- You're going to have,

00:45:15.730 --> 00:45:18.300
as other panelists have talked
about, in refrigerators and,

00:45:18.300 --> 00:45:22.240
you know, operating your lights,
your-- everything about your home,

00:45:22.240 --> 00:45:26.030
it's increasingly becoming-- You
know, we're enveloped in a system

00:45:26.030 --> 00:45:27.620
of artificial intelligence,

00:45:27.620 --> 00:45:29.470
of people doing everything
you can possibly imagine,

00:45:29.470 --> 00:45:32.890
automatically driving
cars, managing your--

00:45:32.890 --> 00:45:38.140
I spent $825 yesterday on getting a
pollution control device in my car.

00:45:38.140 --> 00:45:39.560
It's probably an aftermarket part.

00:45:39.560 --> 00:45:40.860
I have to check.

00:45:40.860 --> 00:45:46.810
I think that you've got this--
You've got this sort of bad model

00:45:46.810 --> 00:45:51.480
for regulating much more than what
people anticipated 20 years ago.

00:45:51.480 --> 00:45:53.320
And I think that you
just have to sort of--

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:57.190
You have to sort of get back
and take a different approach.

00:45:57.190 --> 00:45:59.210
You should have to prove
that you get the benefits

00:45:59.210 --> 00:46:02.340
of the technical protection from
the government, not just assume

00:46:02.340 --> 00:46:04.620
that it's there and then
you have to work backwards.

00:46:04.620 --> 00:46:05.920
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:46:05.920 --> 00:46:07.840
I think Mr. Turnbull is next.

00:46:07.840 --> 00:46:10.570
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: I want
to make a couple of points.

00:46:10.570 --> 00:46:14.820
One, while we have no
opinion on the sort of things

00:46:14.820 --> 00:46:18.920
that are clearly distinct-- I
mean, the auto parts sector--

00:46:18.920 --> 00:46:23.900
the concern that we do have is in
drawing the line between functional

00:46:23.900 --> 00:46:27.800
and expressive, you could
unintentionally sort

00:46:27.800 --> 00:46:30.140
of go too far the other
way, if you will.

00:46:30.140 --> 00:46:36.300
And that is that in a DVD
player or a Blu-ray player,

00:46:36.300 --> 00:46:41.360
what plays the content
is a computer program.

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:45.570
And so-- And it is subject
to certain requirements

00:46:45.570 --> 00:46:48.930
under our licensing agreements
that require that it be robust

00:46:48.930 --> 00:46:51.540
against attack in and of itself.

00:46:51.540 --> 00:46:55.710
What AACS and DVD CCA
provide are specifications

00:46:55.710 --> 00:46:58.370
for how those individual
programs would be developed.

00:46:58.370 --> 00:47:03.120
And so, if you-- If you simply
draw the line and say, well,

00:47:03.120 --> 00:47:08.090
the content itself, the
expressive work that's encrypted

00:47:08.090 --> 00:47:11.240
on the Blu-ray is protected
but the computer program

00:47:11.240 --> 00:47:15.530
that plays it is not, that has the
effect of defeating our system.

00:47:15.530 --> 00:47:18.880
And we would-- we would be
very concerned about that.

00:47:18.880 --> 00:47:22.450
And so, I think in drawing whatever
lines anybody is going to draw,

00:47:22.450 --> 00:47:26.980
that I think needs to be
very carefully preserved,

00:47:26.980 --> 00:47:33.940
that the functionality that
actually enables the playback

00:47:33.940 --> 00:47:38.340
of the expressive content
needs to be protected as well.

00:47:38.340 --> 00:47:45.500
The other point I wanted to make
is that something that both DVD CCA

00:47:45.500 --> 00:47:52.060 position:56%
and AACS LA have offered and has
never been taken up on is for people

00:47:52.060 --> 00:47:55.430
who are interested
in various exemptions

00:47:55.430 --> 00:47:58.580
or various functionalities
that are the subject

00:47:58.580 --> 00:48:03.240
of exemption requests periodically
ought to come talk to us about ways

00:48:03.240 --> 00:48:06.930
in which this could be done
voluntarily and through tools

00:48:06.930 --> 00:48:12.250
that we could cooperatively develop
and could be licensed and agreed

00:48:12.250 --> 00:48:15.900
to by the technology providers.

00:48:15.900 --> 00:48:21.650
And you know, we've periodically
made efforts to do some on our own.

00:48:21.650 --> 00:48:25.480
But we would certainly be
open to cooperative efforts.

00:48:25.480 --> 00:48:27.950
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Are you suggesting
you could license some sort

00:48:27.950 --> 00:48:29.460
of a tool that would allow--

00:48:29.460 --> 00:48:32.990
that would otherwise be
implicated by 1201(b)?

00:48:32.990 --> 00:48:34.290
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: Yes.

00:48:34.290 --> 00:48:38.930 position:56%
Well, not-- You would not-- I mean,
it wouldn't be implicated by 1201(b)

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:40.230
because it would be licensed.

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:46.080
So-- but for example, a number
of the exemptions have had to do

00:48:46.080 --> 00:48:50.670
with short for-- you know,
clips, short portions of films

00:48:50.670 --> 00:48:52.850
that are on DVD or Blu-ray.

00:48:52.850 --> 00:48:58.190
There could be a tool that could
be developed that would enable

00:48:58.190 --> 00:49:02.860
that specifically and wouldn't
have people using tools that are--

00:49:02.860 --> 00:49:06.620
that are copying the entire movie.

00:49:06.620 --> 00:49:09.970
And there are various kinds of
ways that that could be done.

00:49:09.970 --> 00:49:12.030
And you know, I'm not saying
that it would be easy or simple.

00:49:12.030 --> 00:49:16.750
But there are ways that I think
that working together those kinds

00:49:16.750 --> 00:49:18.150
of things could be developed.

00:49:18.150 --> 00:49:22.290 position:56%
And then, they could be presented
as part of an exemption if that was,

00:49:22.290 --> 00:49:23.800
you know, important aspect of it.

00:49:23.800 --> 00:49:26.410 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Making it harder for
Mr. Butler to get Handbrake maybe.

00:49:26.410 --> 00:49:27.710
&gt;&gt; Bruce Turnbull: Yes, yeah.

00:49:27.710 --> 00:49:29.010
Yeah.

00:49:29.010 --> 00:49:30.310
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: OK.

00:49:30.310 --> 00:49:31.610
I want to steer the
conversation a little bit back

00:49:31.610 --> 00:49:32.910
to Kevin's earlier question,

00:49:32.910 --> 00:49:35.390
which was what can we learn
from the Unlocking Act.

00:49:35.390 --> 00:49:38.750
And I notice Mr. Perry said
the proposed class 21 was

00:49:38.750 --> 00:49:42.710 position:56%
for an exemption for the auto
industry, auto repair for actions by

00:49:42.710 --> 00:49:44.010
or on behalf of an owner.

00:49:44.010 --> 00:49:47.260
The Unlocking Act, that language
said that circumvention in the case

00:49:47.260 --> 00:49:50.650
of unlocking cell phones may be
initiated by the owner of any

00:49:50.650 --> 00:49:54.420
such device or by another person
at the direction of the owner.

00:49:54.420 --> 00:49:57.760
So I'm wondering, you know,
we can both think big in terms

00:49:57.760 --> 00:49:59.320
of perhaps there's actions

00:49:59.320 --> 00:50:02.160
that would require some
sort of statutory reform.

00:50:02.160 --> 00:50:04.710
But what are people's opinions

00:50:04.710 --> 00:50:09.460
on whether the triennial rulemaking
process should extend to language

00:50:09.460 --> 00:50:11.400
such as status or risk,
is there a benefit?

00:50:11.400 --> 00:50:12.700
Mr. Adler?

00:50:12.700 --> 00:50:14.000
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: Yeah.

00:50:14.000 --> 00:50:15.300
I think we should be very careful--

00:50:15.300 --> 00:50:17.770
We need to be very
careful about generalizing

00:50:17.770 --> 00:50:22.080
or extrapolating broadly
from what Congress was doing

00:50:22.080 --> 00:50:23.960
with respect to that legislation.

00:50:23.960 --> 00:50:29.280
And the reason is, is because
the legislation was passed only

00:50:29.280 --> 00:50:33.160
after Congress had satisfied
itself that by permitting

00:50:33.160 --> 00:50:34.680
such third party assistance,

00:50:34.680 --> 00:50:38.470
they were not threatening
anyone's copyrighted works.

00:50:38.470 --> 00:50:40.580
Representative of that,
this is a statement

00:50:40.580 --> 00:50:42.770
from the House Judiciary
Committee report.

00:50:42.770 --> 00:50:44.070
It says, "Circumvention

00:50:44.070 --> 00:50:47.780
for unlocking does not compromise
the security of the information

00:50:47.780 --> 00:50:52.640
on the phone and it does not expose
any copyrighted works present

00:50:52.640 --> 00:50:55.470
on the phone to increased
risk of infringement.

00:50:55.470 --> 00:50:58.050
Legalization of circumvention
that has

00:50:58.050 --> 00:51:01.800
such harmful effects is not
the intent of this legislation

00:51:01.800 --> 00:51:06.320
and it would not be
authorized by its provisions."

00:51:06.320 --> 00:51:09.500
The Senate Judiciary Committee
said the same thing in its report.

00:51:09.500 --> 00:51:10.800
So--

00:51:10.800 --> 00:51:12.100
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Can I just--

00:51:12.100 --> 00:51:13.400
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: -- they
set a pretty high bar

00:51:13.400 --> 00:51:14.850
by determining before they acted

00:51:14.850 --> 00:51:18.190
that what they were
authorizing was not in fact going

00:51:18.190 --> 00:51:21.680
to threaten infringement
of any copyrighted work.

00:51:21.680 --> 00:51:22.980
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Can I just ask,

00:51:22.980 --> 00:51:26.440
so what sort of evidence would
be useful or relevant to making

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:27.890
that sort of determination?

00:51:27.890 --> 00:51:33.500
I mean, would we look to sort
of the prevalence of claims

00:51:33.500 --> 00:51:38.280
that are targeting services
rather than devices?

00:51:38.280 --> 00:51:44.560
I mean, in sort of evaluating
whether permitting third party

00:51:44.560 --> 00:51:48.320
assistance would threaten
a particular market, what--

00:51:48.320 --> 00:51:49.890
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: I mean, over
time, we would be looking

00:51:49.890 --> 00:51:51.290
at those kinds of claims.

00:51:51.290 --> 00:51:56.460
We would see ultimately whether
or not there would be instances

00:51:56.460 --> 00:52:00.280
where allegations of
infringement resulting

00:52:00.280 --> 00:52:03.130
from circumvention
could be traced back

00:52:03.130 --> 00:52:05.860
to what had been authorized
by the legislation.

00:52:05.860 --> 00:52:09.620 position:56%
I think what Congress did in this
instance and what anybody would have

00:52:09.620 --> 00:52:14.970
to do in being a proponent of
such third party assistance is

00:52:14.970 --> 00:52:19.500
to actually think through in
fact what is being circumvented

00:52:19.500 --> 00:52:23.840
and what are the consequences
of that specific circumvention.

00:52:23.840 --> 00:52:25.450
That's what Congress did.

00:52:25.450 --> 00:52:27.920
And it was precisely
because it determined

00:52:27.920 --> 00:52:33.060
that that authorized circumvention,
done even by third parties,

00:52:33.060 --> 00:52:37.960
would not allow them to expose any
copyrighted works to infringement,

00:52:37.960 --> 00:52:41.300
was the reason that Congress felt
comfortable authorizing that.

00:52:41.300 --> 00:52:42.600
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: So would
that be an argument

00:52:42.600 --> 00:52:46.900
for allowing the Copyright Office
to make a similar assessment

00:52:46.900 --> 00:52:48.700
within the rulemaking or--

00:52:48.700 --> 00:52:50.000
&gt;&gt; Allan Adler: No,
quite the contrary.

00:52:50.000 --> 00:52:53.070
I think that this is a task that
only Congress should be permitted

00:52:53.070 --> 00:52:57.630
to do because it is so
significant in terms

00:52:57.630 --> 00:52:59.490
of its potential implications.

00:52:59.490 --> 00:53:03.160
And I think it's not something
that can simply be delegated

00:53:03.160 --> 00:53:05.420
to either the Register
or the Librarian.

00:53:05.420 --> 00:53:07.380
And if I may just add one
other thought in response

00:53:07.380 --> 00:53:09.520
to what my friend Brandon
said before, I mean,

00:53:09.520 --> 00:53:14.530
we're very sympathetic to the whole
notion about libraries, archives,

00:53:14.530 --> 00:53:18.560 position:56%
academic institutions wanting to
preserve the works that are produced

00:53:18.560 --> 00:53:21.750
by the people in my
industry and others.

00:53:21.750 --> 00:53:24.530
But there is another avenue
for them to pursue that.

00:53:24.530 --> 00:53:26.710
As the Copyright Office well knows,

00:53:26.710 --> 00:53:29.940
a few years ago there was a
very comprehensive study done

00:53:29.940 --> 00:53:32.660
of section 108 of the Copyright Act

00:53:32.660 --> 00:53:36.940
which specifically would have
allowed for addressing questions

00:53:36.940 --> 00:53:40.670
about digital preservation,
including preservation of works

00:53:40.670 --> 00:53:43.560
that only exist in digital form.

00:53:43.560 --> 00:53:47.980
And we have been interested
in seeing that study pursued,

00:53:47.980 --> 00:53:49.390
because we're not looking

00:53:49.390 --> 00:53:52.610
to essentially leave
these institutions locked

00:53:52.610 --> 00:53:55.720
into 20th century technology
capabilities

00:53:55.720 --> 00:53:57.540
with respect to preservation.

00:53:57.540 --> 00:54:01.000
But there again, you'd be
talking about first the question

00:54:01.000 --> 00:54:05.260
of preservation and then
secondly, preservation to what end.

00:54:05.260 --> 00:54:10.400
Simply the end of access to
those works ultimately being what

00:54:10.400 --> 00:54:14.090 position:56%
preservation is about, you would
have to be able to determine whether

00:54:14.090 --> 00:54:17.230
in fact being able to
circumvent in order

00:54:17.230 --> 00:54:21.940
to preserve those works is simply
going to allow access by scholars

00:54:21.940 --> 00:54:24.600
and students, faculty,
others who are using them

00:54:24.600 --> 00:54:29.130
for legitimate purposes or would
the access policies subsequently

00:54:29.130 --> 00:54:32.150
threaten infringement in a way
that might question whether

00:54:32.150 --> 00:54:36.640
or not circumvention needed to
be more tightly [inaudible].

00:54:36.640 --> 00:54:37.940
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Thank you.

00:54:37.940 --> 00:54:39.240
Mr. Butler?

00:54:39.240 --> 00:54:41.780
&gt;&gt; Brandon Butler: Oh, boy.

00:54:41.780 --> 00:54:48.190
Yeah, so I wanted to-- I'll resist
responding to Allan for a minute.

00:54:48.190 --> 00:54:52.810
I wanted to come back to something
else briefly, which is another sort

00:54:52.810 --> 00:54:57.970
of risk in the question
of whether the beneficiary

00:54:57.970 --> 00:55:01.050 position:56%
of an exemption is going to actually
get the benefit of the exemption.

00:55:01.050 --> 00:55:04.280
That's I think a relatively
new risk is the question

00:55:04.280 --> 00:55:09.340
of whether the Office will
itself or will ask the proponents

00:55:09.340 --> 00:55:14.040
of an exemption to very
narrowly tailor that exemption

00:55:14.040 --> 00:55:19.070
so that it steers far clear of
any connection to trafficking,

00:55:19.070 --> 00:55:21.660
because I think there are--

00:55:21.660 --> 00:55:26.400
there are activities that we would
say are clearly not trafficking.

00:55:26.400 --> 00:55:29.580
So, you know, again,
internal assistance, right?

00:55:29.580 --> 00:55:36.740
So if an AV librarian is asked by
a faculty member to, you know, to--

00:55:36.740 --> 00:55:39.760
how to make a clip-- I'm
entitled to make a clip.

00:55:39.760 --> 00:55:41.060
How do I do it?

00:55:41.060 --> 00:55:42.360
What do I use?

00:55:42.360 --> 00:55:44.780
That's something that we think
is not third party assistance.

00:55:44.780 --> 00:55:46.080
It's not trafficking.

00:55:46.080 --> 00:55:47.380
It's all internal.

00:55:47.380 --> 00:55:51.880
If a documentary filmmaker has
an AV staff person on the staff

00:55:51.880 --> 00:55:56.940
of that film, but-- and the wording
of the exemptions in the past--

00:55:56.940 --> 00:56:00.550
in the 2010 and in
the 2012 iterations

00:56:00.550 --> 00:56:05.470
of the education exception
was nicely crafted I think.

00:56:05.470 --> 00:56:08.570
Actually and this is I think
probably on me and my students.

00:56:08.570 --> 00:56:11.350
We diverged from that
crafting for reasons

00:56:11.350 --> 00:56:12.970
that are lost now to
the mists of time.

00:56:12.970 --> 00:56:16.620
But there was a nice crafting that
said sort of the person engaging

00:56:16.620 --> 00:56:21.070
in the circumvention would be
allowed to circumvent for purposes

00:56:21.070 --> 00:56:24.740
of allowing educational uses
by faculty and students.

00:56:24.740 --> 00:56:28.800
So that distinction between the
person and the faculty made plenty

00:56:28.800 --> 00:56:31.600
of room in the plain
text for a librarian.

