01:09:29.610 --> 01:09:33.220
to do what they want to do,
the problem is that those--

01:09:33.220 --> 01:09:35.820
especially as to devices
or pieces of software,

01:09:35.820 --> 01:09:38.340
obviously can't differentiate
between the legitimate

01:09:38.340 --> 01:09:41.280
and the illegitimate uses, at
least as to motion pictures.

01:09:41.280 --> 01:09:44.290
I mean, once you put it on
the shelf at Walmart, yes,

01:09:44.290 --> 01:09:48.280
you might have people-- you
know, Mr. Butler may be able and,

01:09:48.280 --> 01:09:51.140
you know, his colleagues would
use it for legitimate purposes

01:09:51.140 --> 01:09:52.900
under the, you know,
under the exemptions

01:09:52.900 --> 01:09:54.200
that they've been granted.

01:09:54.200 --> 01:09:57.230
But probably the vast majority
of consumers would think, hey,

01:09:57.230 --> 01:09:58.600
here's a piece of software.

01:09:58.600 --> 01:10:01.980
It says that I can rip
DVDs and Blu-ray players.

01:10:01.980 --> 01:10:03.280
That sounds kind of nifty.

01:10:03.280 --> 01:10:04.580
I should be able to do that.

01:10:04.580 --> 01:10:08.480 position:56%
And it actually sort of-- It
confuses consumers and misleads them

01:10:08.480 --> 01:10:12.310
into thinking that it's a
legitimate activity where it's not.

01:10:12.310 --> 01:10:15.120 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: I just wonder though,
you know, where does that leave us

01:10:15.120 --> 01:10:21.090
and is there any sort of
proposal that you would suggest?

01:10:21.090 --> 01:10:25.830
I mean, just sort of anecdotally
at least, it would seem plausible

01:10:25.830 --> 01:10:33.230
to conclude that there, you
know, is a material set of people

01:10:33.230 --> 01:10:37.020
who are beneficiaries of exemptions
who, just as a practical matter,

01:10:37.020 --> 01:10:41.820
don't have the technical
capability to circumvent.

01:10:41.820 --> 01:10:44.770
So I just wonder are we stuck just

01:10:44.770 --> 01:10:47.330
without any sort of
possible solution?

01:10:47.330 --> 01:10:51.320 position:56%
I mean, I think one thing that we've
suggested is, well, what, you know--

01:10:51.320 --> 01:10:53.590
could we be granted
authority to at least consider

01:10:53.590 --> 01:10:55.330
that as part of the rulemaking?

01:10:55.330 --> 01:10:58.550
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Well, I would
say at least as to motion pictures

01:10:58.550 --> 01:11:01.560
and the exemptions that have been
granted as to audiovisual works,

01:11:01.560 --> 01:11:02.860
I actually don't think
there's a problem.

01:11:02.860 --> 01:11:05.840
I mean, I think Mr. Butler
acknowledged them, you know,

01:11:05.840 --> 01:11:08.060
a few minutes ago, and I
wrote down what he said.

01:11:08.060 --> 01:11:12.790 position:56%
He said, with quote, "We haven't
been terribly deterred from engaging

01:11:12.790 --> 01:11:16.750 position:56%
in the activity which is
authorized by the exemptions that he

01:11:16.750 --> 01:11:18.140
and his colleagues
have been granted."

01:11:18.140 --> 01:11:19.440
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Yeah,
but-- And is he talking

01:11:19.440 --> 01:11:21.710
about prohibited activity or--

01:11:21.710 --> 01:11:24.390
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Well, I'm not
saying that he's been engaged.

01:11:24.390 --> 01:11:25.690
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Well, right.

01:11:25.690 --> 01:11:27.130
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Or
that-- And I don't think--

01:11:27.130 --> 01:11:28.730
and frankly, by going--
by going off--

01:11:28.730 --> 01:11:30.340
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: But I mean, I
think that's the argument, right?

01:11:30.340 --> 01:11:32.780
I mean, that you're
just sort of, you know,

01:11:32.780 --> 01:11:35.960 position:56%
encouraging people to break the law.

01:11:35.960 --> 01:11:37.610
&gt;&gt; Ben Sheffner: Well,
I don't believe

01:11:37.610 --> 01:11:41.350
that I've accused Mr.
Butler of breaking the law.

01:11:41.350 --> 01:11:45.260
What I've acknowledged is the
practical reality that he is able

01:11:45.260 --> 01:11:49.690
to go and find tools to do
what he's been authorized to do

01:11:49.690 --> 01:11:52.630
by the Copyright Office
and that the other--

01:11:52.630 --> 01:11:55.010
the other option, which
is to say, OK,

01:11:55.010 --> 01:11:56.700
well he's been granted
the exemption,

01:11:56.700 --> 01:12:00.760 position:56%
therefore there should be, you
know, a lawful market in trafficking

01:12:00.760 --> 01:12:04.330
and anti-circumvention
devices, has worse results,

01:12:04.330 --> 01:12:08.660
has worse consequences,
that look at--

01:12:08.660 --> 01:12:11.940
that I will say that the
situation today isn't perfect.

01:12:11.940 --> 01:12:15.950
But the alternative of permitting,
you know, a legitimate market

01:12:15.950 --> 01:12:19.990
in circumvention devices or
software would be much worse.

01:12:19.990 --> 01:12:21.850
And it would just mainstream
that activity

01:12:21.850 --> 01:12:26.760
and in a sense swallow the rule
against circumvention itself.

01:12:26.760 --> 01:12:28.060
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: OK.

01:12:28.060 --> 01:12:29.360
Thank you.

01:12:29.360 --> 01:12:30.660
Mr. Schwartz?

01:12:30.660 --> 01:12:31.960
&gt;&gt; Robert S. Schwartz: Well,
just as a rhetorical question,

01:12:31.960 --> 01:12:35.320
