infringement by circumvention.

01:15:43.080 --> 01:15:47.890
I was wondering if I could get your
thoughts on that as an alternative.

01:15:47.890 --> 01:15:53.540
&gt;&gt; Kevin Amer: Just-- I know
there were a couple of cards up.

01:15:53.540 --> 01:15:56.490
If you all wanted to respond
to previous questions,

01:15:56.490 --> 01:16:00.720
I think feel free to do so, while
others can think about a response

01:16:00.720 --> 01:16:03.530
to the proposed legislation.

01:16:03.530 --> 01:16:05.770
So, Mr. Butler?

01:16:05.770 --> 01:16:07.070
&gt;&gt; Brandon Butler: Sure.

01:16:07.070 --> 01:16:12.010 position:56%
So just to sort of revise and extend
my remarks from a minute ago, the--

01:16:12.010 --> 01:16:17.040 position:56%
while Handbrake seems to work fairly
well, a problem that we've seen--

01:16:17.040 --> 01:16:19.720
and a general problem that we've
seen in all of these panels

01:16:19.720 --> 01:16:22.610
from beneficiaries is we
don't know what we don't know

01:16:22.610 --> 01:16:27.530
about how much better these things
could be, how harmed we are,

01:16:27.530 --> 01:16:31.720 position:56%
what we can and can't do because
our behaviors are shaped by the law.

01:16:31.720 --> 01:16:33.640
So we have Handbrake.

01:16:33.640 --> 01:16:35.400
Handbrake does what Handbrake does.

01:16:35.400 --> 01:16:36.830
That seems to be great.

01:16:36.830 --> 01:16:42.820 position:56%
We don't know what someone would do
if Mr. Turnbull were to license them

01:16:42.820 --> 01:16:45.490
and they were to take full
advantage or if they were

01:16:45.490 --> 01:16:47.330
to get the benefit of an exemption.

01:16:47.330 --> 01:16:49.190
We don't know what the
market would do in terms

01:16:49.190 --> 01:16:50.750
of generating better tools.

01:16:50.750 --> 01:16:55.260
We also-- We just got an exemption
for Blu-ray, and Blu-ray is harder.

01:16:55.260 --> 01:16:59.190
And I'm actually looking forward
in a perverse way, looking for a,

01:16:59.190 --> 01:17:01.590
you know, I'm curious
what will happen.

01:17:01.590 --> 01:17:03.370
Will people really get to use it?

01:17:03.370 --> 01:17:04.670
Because it is harder.

01:17:04.670 --> 01:17:05.970
It takes longer.

01:17:05.970 --> 01:17:07.270
It's a big file.

01:17:07.270 --> 01:17:08.570
There are sort of two or three
different software processes

01:17:08.570 --> 01:17:09.870
involved in the ripping.

01:17:09.870 --> 01:17:12.630
So how will that work
as easily as DVD.

01:17:12.630 --> 01:17:16.040
And then, of course, in the
future what's going to happen?

01:17:16.040 --> 01:17:18.280
And none of this stuff is going
to be on the shelf at Walmart.

01:17:18.280 --> 01:17:20.760
And so, if that's what we're
worried about, let's, you know,

01:17:20.760 --> 01:17:23.680
open the floodgates for
the specialized users

01:17:23.680 --> 01:17:26.670
because they're not-- You know,
mechanics don't shop at Walmart

01:17:26.670 --> 01:17:29.190
for the products that
they need to rip cars.

01:17:29.190 --> 01:17:31.320
We don't shop at Walmart for
the products that we need.

01:17:31.320 --> 01:17:33.850
You know, the digital
preservation librarian

01:17:33.850 --> 01:17:37.860
at UVA has this huge bizarre
computer tower thing that has all

01:17:37.860 --> 01:17:39.180
of these obsolete drives in it.

01:17:39.180 --> 01:17:40.660
It's a specialized tool.

01:17:40.660 --> 01:17:42.880
That's the kind of stuff that
we buy and we shop from people

01:17:42.880 --> 01:17:44.180
who sell that kind of stuff.

01:17:44.180 --> 01:17:45.480
And it's not Walmart.

01:17:45.480 --> 01:17:46.820
So that might be helpful.

01:17:46.820 --> 01:17:48.120
Maybe there's some consensus here.

01:17:48.120 --> 01:17:50.210
If we can keep it out of
Walmart, it's all good.

01:17:50.210 --> 01:17:51.510
&gt;&gt; Regan Smith: Ms. Besek?

01:17:51.510 --> 01:17:57.220
&gt;&gt; June Besek: I just want
to make a couple of points.

01:17:57.220 --> 01:18:00.390
One is on the power of
the Copyright Office

01:18:00.390 --> 01:18:05.140
to allow circumvention
services or tools.

01:18:05.140 --> 01:18:09.730
You know, I heard the quote
from legislative history.

01:18:09.730 --> 01:18:12.550
But first of all, that was
a statement on the floor.

01:18:12.550 --> 01:18:16.200
So I think we have to take
that as that individual's view.

01:18:16.200 --> 01:18:18.860
And secondly, legislative
history one only resorts

01:18:18.860 --> 01:18:20.350
to if the statute isn't clear.

01:18:20.350 --> 01:18:22.780
And I think in this case,
the statute is fairly clear.

01:18:22.780 --> 01:18:25.050
So that's obviously the
first place you go to,

01:18:25.050 --> 01:18:26.730
to understand the statute.

01:18:26.730 --> 01:18:30.980
The other point I want to
make is about the functional

01:18:30.980 --> 01:18:33.650
versus expressive approach.

01:18:33.650 --> 01:18:35.630
I've been in copyright
now for 30 years

01:18:35.630 --> 01:18:38.000
and I really never thought
I'd spend as much time talking

01:18:38.000 --> 01:18:40.790
about automobile repair
as we have today.

01:18:40.790 --> 01:18:43.900
And I find it a little
disconcerting.

01:18:43.900 --> 01:18:49.000
And I am-- I really would not want
decisions about automobile repair

01:18:49.000 --> 01:18:53.190
and replacement parts to
drive-- no pun intended--

01:18:53.190 --> 01:18:56.310
the decisions about circumvention,

01:18:56.310 --> 01:18:59.530
circumvention devices,
circumvention services.

01:18:59.530 --> 01:19:03.710
And if that means ultimately
there has to be some distinction

01:19:03.710 --> 01:19:07.780
between software that governs
functional works and then,

01:19:07.780 --> 01:19:09.880 position:56%
on the other hand, expressive works.

01:19:09.880 --> 01:19:13.830 position:56%
And on that expressive works side, I
would add anything that has to deal

01:19:13.830 --> 01:19:16.600
with any kind of playback device.

01:19:16.600 --> 01:19:18.530
Then maybe that's the
route we have to go on.

01:19:18.530 --> 01:19:22.720
But if-- you know, I'm concerned
that, you know, there is a lot

01:19:22.720 --> 01:19:27.180
of understandable concern
on the part of the public

01:19:27.180 --> 01:19:28.480
about not being able

01:19:28.480 --> 01:19:31.820
to get replacement parts
for functional devices.

01:19:31.820 --> 01:19:39.050
And if that is going to affect
the rules that govern, you know,

01:19:39.050 --> 01:19:44.300
books on e-book readers and movies
and all those kinds of things,

01:19:44.300 --> 01:19:46.630
then I think that we have to
jettison some of those things

01:19:46.630 --> 01:19:47.930
or treat them separately.

01:19:47.930 --> 01:19:52.780
Because I don't think
that ultimately

01:19:52.780 --> 01:19:56.300
that copyright interests are
going to win the hearts and minds

01:19:56.300 --> 01:19:59.030
of the American people on this.

