01:20:47.320 --> 01:20:54.570
&gt;&gt; James Love: I would agree with
Professor Besek's comment about,

01:20:54.570 --> 01:20:56.060
you know, not worried about the--

01:20:56.060 --> 01:20:59.780
about, you know, like the
automobile industry sort

01:20:59.780 --> 01:21:01.080
of driving the copyright thing.

01:21:01.080 --> 01:21:04.130 position:56%
You could also turn that on its head
and you could sort of say, you know,

01:21:04.130 --> 01:21:06.440
the rest of the economy maybe
doesn't want the motion picture

01:21:06.440 --> 01:21:10.220
industry and, you know,
the book industry

01:21:10.220 --> 01:21:12.840
to drive the rest of
the economy either.

01:21:12.840 --> 01:21:15.940
I think that the marriage
between these two things is--

01:21:15.940 --> 01:21:19.720
I would agree it is problematic.

01:21:19.720 --> 01:21:21.550
I go back to the idea on the act.

01:21:21.550 --> 01:21:27.170
I think it'd be good if you imagine
at least two tiers of approaches,

01:21:27.170 --> 01:21:31.720 position:56%
one for areas where you think maybe
the whole regime is kind of intended

01:21:31.720 --> 01:21:35.780
for in the first instance and
where people feel comfortable

01:21:35.780 --> 01:21:38.010
that they're kind of working
towards solutions in that area.

01:21:38.010 --> 01:21:42.360 position:56%
And then, a second area where kind
of the collateral damage of the DMC,

01:21:42.360 --> 01:21:46.180
you know, where automobile
sector, medical devices,

01:21:46.180 --> 01:21:49.580
garage door openers, inkjet
cartridges, all that sort of stuff.

01:21:49.580 --> 01:21:53.540
And then-- and that you
begin again the process

01:21:53.540 --> 01:21:56.150
of not treating everything
exactly the same.

01:21:56.150 --> 01:21:58.630
In Europe-- By the way, in that
licensing issue that was brought

01:21:58.630 --> 01:22:02.010
up before-- in Europe,
there's an obligation in the--

01:22:02.010 --> 01:22:07.920
for copyright owners
to take measures

01:22:07.920 --> 01:22:10.530
that make exceptions
available to people.

01:22:10.530 --> 01:22:14.580
It isn't really clear what happens
if they don't take those measures.

01:22:14.580 --> 01:22:17.280
But it's sort of-- You know, there
is an affirmative obligation.

01:22:17.280 --> 01:22:20.000 position:56%
I don't think there's any obligation
like that in the US system

01:22:20.000 --> 01:22:21.300
and I think that's a mistake.

01:22:21.300 --> 01:22:25.570
If you really want the automobile
manufacturers to license people

01:22:25.570 --> 01:22:27.840
to compete against them
and sell cheaper parts

01:22:27.840 --> 01:22:30.440
than the automobile manufacturer
wants to charge themselves

01:22:30.440 --> 01:22:32.040
and they have no obligation
to do so,

01:22:32.040 --> 01:22:35.240
I don't see why they
would want to do that.

01:22:35.240 --> 01:22:41.070
And so, this idea that people
within a sector should have

01:22:41.070 --> 01:22:45.490 position:56%
to have an affirmative obligation to
license the technology or the tools

01:22:45.490 --> 01:22:48.510
or whatever like that to address
something is a first step,

01:22:48.510 --> 01:22:51.650
but also puts an obligation on
people that are seeking to traffic

01:22:51.650 --> 01:22:53.460
in devices and things
like that to pursue

01:22:53.460 --> 01:22:55.360
that opportunity before they resort

01:22:55.360 --> 01:22:58.200
to their own do-it-yourself
kind of remedies as well.

01:22:58.200 --> 01:23:01.830
That may be kind of a
compromise where you have a step

01:23:01.830 --> 01:23:04.480
where the people that are
affected the most by it have--

01:23:04.480 --> 01:23:07.980
you know, have to be approached,
work out the basic details,

01:23:07.980 --> 01:23:10.340
understand kind of what the
parameters and the debate are.

01:23:10.340 --> 01:23:13.720
